example.p:
We have the coefficient matrix for Archetype and a row-equivalent matrix B in reduced row-echelon form.A=\begin{bmatrix}
            1 & -1 & 2\\
            2 & 1 & 1\\
            1 & 1 & 0
            \end{bmatrix}
            \rref\begin{bmatrix}
            \leading{1} & 0 & 1\\
            0 & \leading{1} & -1\\
            0 & 0 & 0
            \end{bmatrix}=BSince B is not the 3\times 3 identity matrix,  tells us that A is a singular matrix.

We have the coefficient matrix for Archetype and a row-equivalent matrix B in reduced row-echelon form.A=\begin{bmatrix}
            -7&-6&-12\\
             5&5&7\\
             1&0&4
            \end{bmatrix}
            \rref\begin{bmatrix}
             \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
             0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
             0 & 0 & \leading{1}
            \end{bmatrix}
            =BSince B is the 3\times 3 identity matrix,  tells us that A is a nonsingular matrix.

Given the singular coefficient matrix from Archetype, the null space is the set of solutions to the homogeneous system of equations \homosystem{A}, which has a solution set and null space constructed in  as an infinite set of vectors.
                A&=\begin{bmatrix}
                1 & -1 & 2\\
                2 & 1 & 1\\
                1 & 1 & 0
                \end{bmatrix}
                &\nsp{A}
                &=\setparts{\colvector{-x_3\\x_3\\x_3}}{x_3\in\complexes}

Given the nonsingular coefficient matrix from Archetype, the solution set to the homogeneous system \homosystem{A} is constructed in  and contains only the trivial solution, so the null space of A has only a single element.
                A&=\begin{bmatrix}
                -7&-6&-12\\
                 5&5&7\\
                 1&0&4
                \end{bmatrix}
                &\nsp{A}
                &=\set{\colvector{0\\0\\0}}

solution.p:
The matrix row-reduces to\begin{bmatrix}
                        \leading{1}&  0 &  0 &  0\\
                        0 & \leading{1} &  0 &  0\\
                        0 &  0 & \leading{1} &  0\\
                        0 &  0 &  0 & \leading{1}
                        \end{bmatrix}which is the 4\times 4 identity matrix.  By  the original matrix must be nonsingular.

tells us we can answer this question by simply row-reducing the matrix.  Doing this we obtain\begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
                    0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0 \\
                    0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0 \\
                    0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                   \end{bmatrix}.  Since the reduced row-echelon form of the matrix is the 4\times 4 identity matrix I_4, we know that B is nonsingular.

We row-reduce the coefficient matrix of the system of equations.
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     -1 & 5 & 0 & 0  \\
                     -2 & 5 & 5 & 2  \\
                     -3 & -1 & 3 & 1  \\
                     7 & 6 & 5 & 1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &\rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0  \\
                     0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0  \\
                     0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0  \\
                     0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                    \end{bmatrix}
